## Building a Skeleton Loader in Angular

**Mental model:** A skeleton is a grey placeholder shaped like the loading content, with a moving shimmer. Build one `app-skeleton` primitive (width/height/radius inputs) and compose it into a card. Swap skeleton ↔ content on a `loading` flag with `*ngIf`/`else`. Classic `NgModule` setup, no `?.`/`??` (the build rejects them).

### Step 1 — A primitive skeleton component
```typescript
@Component({ selector: 'app-skeleton', template: `<span class="skeleton" [style.width]="width" [style.height]="height" [style.border-radius]="radius"></span>`, styles: [/* shimmer */] })
export class SkeletonComponent {
  @Input() width = '100%';
  @Input() height = '16px';
  @Input() radius = '4px';
}
```

### Step 2 — Animate the shimmer
```css
.skeleton { display: block; background: linear-gradient(90deg, #e5e7eb 25%, #f3f4f6 37%, #e5e7eb 63%); background-size: 400% 100%; animation: shimmer 1.4s ease infinite; }
@keyframes shimmer { 0% { background-position: 100% 0; } 100% { background-position: 0 0; } }
```

### Step 3 — Compose the card skeleton
Mirror the real card so there's no layout shift.

```html
<div class="card"><app-skeleton width="48px" height="48px" radius="50%"></app-skeleton></div>
```

### Step 4 — Swap on the loading flag
```html
<div *ngIf="loading; else loaded" class="card">…skeletons…</div>
<ng-template #loaded><div class="card">…real content…</div></ng-template>
```

**Edge cases**

| Case | Handling |
| :-- | :-- |
| Layout shift | Match skeleton size to real content. |
| Reduced motion | Honour `prefers-reduced-motion`. |
| Fast loads | Delay the skeleton ~200ms to avoid a flash. |

**Interview tip:** A reusable `app-skeleton` with inputs (rather than ad-hoc divs per screen) is the maintainable approach — and the headline point is matching dimensions so content arrival doesn't shift the layout.

